{quote}Version 1.x of source tree shows the 'Labels' of the GIT commit when you select the commit in the history of any repo. 
There could be multiple labels, and the user can very easily text select them for copy and paste.

The version 2.0.x does not display any 'Labels' in the commit description, so you cannot select and copy the text.{quote}

Customer report:

{quote}
I am using a 4K monitor so I have set all of the fonts for my machine to be much larger than what may be considered normal. My assumption is that SourceTree is pulling from that system font size without adjusting cell size to compensate
{quote}

 !image-2017-03-24-12-56-58-316.png|thumbnail!

 

There's a grammar mistake in the error message shown when we enter an invalid cloning path in Sourcetree, when cloning a repository. The current message says:

{{Invalid clone path. Folder must _be exist_ and also be empty}}

Instead, it should say:

{{Invalid clone path. Folder must exist and also be empty}}

This is happening in Windows with SourceTree 1.10.23.1

Customer's report:

\{quote}

When Split view staging is selected for Git repositories, the Mercurial file status view keeps refreshing (maybe trying to stage files) when trying to select which changes to include. Each refresh occurs very quickly after selecting a file to include in a commit and deselects all included changes making it nearly impossible to commit. Changing Git repositories back to no staging allows Mercurial committing to work again.

I'm using beta 2.0.11.1 on Windows which isn't listed below.

\{quote}

[^ScourceTreeSplitViewStaging.mp4]

I've been using SourceTree for a while and never had this problem, but the past 2 days (when I updated the software from `1.9.x` to `1.10.23.1`) I couldn't use it because it was very slowly! Each click action took me 10s+ to process. After 2 days trying different solutions,, for example:
 * Tried this: [http://stackoverflow.com/questions/28105472/sourcetree-very-slow-with-many-repositories;]
 * Tried to change to beta version: Beta `2.0.12-beta-001`;
 * Reinstalled Sourcetree (both 1.10 and Beta);
 * Reinstalled Git (to the lastest version);

But what really solved my problem was disabling the Antivirus (mine is avast). Before 1.10 I used to use SourceTree with antivirus on everything worked fine. But since I updated, it's way too slow.

Don't know if this is actually the problem, but since I disabled it, I had no more problems. Have been using it the whole day and it's normal.

By the way, since the start of the problem, even with just 1 and a new repository just for test, it was slow. So it had nothing to do with huge files, etc...

 

Note: Even when I tried to specify the path to my files to exclude from the antivirus, it had no effect, it was too slow. Only completely disabling the antivirus solve the problem.
